abstract: Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan said on Wednesday Washington and Ankara had done little to solve a row over Turkey's purchase of Russian defenses and its procurement of U.S. fighter jets despite a November agreement, according to broadcaster NTV.
snippet: Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan said on Wednesday Washington and Ankara had done little to solve a row over Turkey's purchase of Russian defenses and its procurement of U.S. fighter jets despite a November agreement, according to broadcaster NTV.
lead_paragraph: ANKARA — Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan said on Wednesday Washington and Ankara had done little to solve a row over Turkey's purchase of Russian defenses and its procurement of U.S. fighter jets despite a November agreement, according to broadcaster NTV.
headline_main: Little U.S.-Turkish Progress Solving Defenses Row, Erdogan Says: NTV
headline_print_headline: Little U.S.-Turkish Progress Solving Defenses Row, Erdogan Says: NTV

abstract: The questioning could go deep into the night.
snippet: The questioning could go deep into the night.
lead_paragraph: The senators wrapped after more than two hours of uninterrupted questions, including the occasional cross-examination by Republicans of the Democratic House managers and by Democrats of President Trump’s lawyers.

abstract: The group that hosted the event last month in Cleveland is run by a prominent black ally of the president, and it promoted Trump administration policies while doling out cash prizes.
snippet: The group that hosted the event last month in Cleveland is run by a prominent black ally of the president, and it promoted Trump administration policies while doling out cash prizes.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A nonprofit organization run by one of President Trump’s most prominent African-American allies recently held an event in a black community where it promoted Trump administration policies like criminal justice reform while doling out cash prizes to participants.

abstract: The Trump administration on Wednesday imposed sanctions on a Moscow-based private railway company that last month opened passenger service between Russia and Crimea, a Ukrainian peninsula that Russia annexed in 2014.
snippet: The Trump administration on Wednesday imposed sanctions on a Moscow-based private railway company that last month opened passenger service between Russia and Crimea, a Ukrainian peninsula that Russia annexed in 2014.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration on Wednesday imposed sanctions on a Moscow-based private railway company that last month opened passenger service between Russia and Crimea, a Ukrainian peninsula that Russia annexed in 2014.
headline_main: US Hits Russian Railroad With Sanctions Over Crimea

abstract: More than a year before the suspension of a Post reporter whose tweet referred to allegations against him, the paper’s journalists complained about how the N.B.A. star was received.
snippet: More than a year before the suspension of a Post reporter whose tweet referred to allegations against him, the paper’s journalists complained about how the N.B.A. star was received.
lead_paragraph: The suspension of a Washington Post reporter who referred to a 2003 sexual assault charge against Kobe Bryant on Twitter in the hours after his death led to an uproar among the newspaper’s staff members.

abstract: A lawyer for President Trump tried to suggest that Mr. Trump’s interest was not prompted by the announcement of former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. in late April that he was running for president.
snippet: A lawyer for President Trump tried to suggest that Mr. Trump’s interest was not prompted by the announcement of former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. in late April that he was running for president.
lead_paragraph: Senators Susan Collins of Maine and Lisa Murkowski of Alaska jointly raised one of the more interesting questions of the afternoon: At what point did President Trump decide that Ukraine needed to investigate former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. and his son, Hunter Biden?

abstract: Efforts to bring wavering Republicans into line appeared to be working as President Trump’s lawyers argued that anything a president did to win re-election was “in the public interest.”
snippet: Efforts to bring wavering Republicans into line appeared to be working as President Trump’s lawyers argued that anything a president did to win re-election was “in the public interest.”
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House and Senate Republicans worked aggressively on Wednesday to discount damaging revelations from John R. Bolton and line up the votes to block new witnesses from testifying in President Trump’s impeachment trial, in a push to bring the proceeding to a swift close.
